               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380514-name-1363" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1363" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1363" type="surname" value="CHAPMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1363" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT CHAPMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a bricklayer, and live in Edward's-lane, Deptford. I was at Greenwich-fair on the 18th of April, about eleven clock, looking at one of the shows—a policeman touched me, and said something—I missed my handkerchief—this is it—(<hi rend="italic">looking at it</hi>.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380514-name-1364" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1364" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1364" type="surname" value="CLARKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1364" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT CLARKE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 167.) On the 18th of April I saw a prisoner between nine and ten o'clock, trying several people's pockets—I went behind the prosecutor, and stood there a few minutes, and then left him—I took him, and he had this handkerchief in his hand—on searching. him, I found three other handkerchiefs.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. Two of the policemen came and took me out of the crowd, and said, "What do you do with this handkerchief?" but I had never seen—it never was in my hand. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. I took it from his hand.</p>
